   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Creating the Neural network architecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "id": "384427cf-8c68-4b2f-b89f-dc8b96e1dea0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# tensorflow, keras, sequential, dense\n",
    "\n",
    "from tensorflow import keras\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras import Sequential\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras.layers import Dense, LSTM, Embedding"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "id": "f561272a-0fd3-47f3-8bd7-082052633751",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "C:\\Users\\bhavy\\anaconda3\\envs\\pybase-TF2.0\\lib\\site-packages\\keras\\src\\layers\\core\\embedding.py:93: UserWarning: Do not pass an `input_shape`/`input_dim` argument to a layer. When using Sequential models, prefer using an `Input(shape)` object as the first layer in the model instead.\n",
      "  super().__init__(**kwargs)\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = Sequential()\n",
    "\n",
    "model.add(Embedding(input_dim=total_vocab_len+1,output_dim=10,input_shape=(max_length,)))\n",
    "\n",
    "# input_dim is the total_vocab_len + 1 (1 is for padding).\n",
    "\n",
    "model.add(LSTM(units=32,dropout=0.2))   # Each sentence now goes word by word to LSTM layer.\n",
    "\n",
    "# Total 494 timesteps, and you get Ht (Hidden) and Ct (Cell state) at each timestep. Ht-1 and Ct-1 are used to get Ht and Ct\n",
    "# The Ht and Ct you get after final timestep are used. Ht is passed to the output layer for rating prediction\n",
    "# In this example, Ct is of no use after last timestep for each sentence (since this is not word prediction). \n",
    "# Thus, Ct is re-calculated for each sentence\n",
    "\n",
    "model.add(Dense(5,activation='softmax'))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2fffb093-c681-4956-8622-60f82940ea8b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "for first sentence:-\n",
    "\n",
    "whole 494 integer list (ie, the sentence) goes to the embedding layer. Shape (494,)\n",
    "\n",
    "Embedding layer gives us 10 dimensional vector for each **word**. Shape (494,10)\n",
    "\n",
    "Now, LSTM is fed with 10 dimensional vectors **word-by-word**, till last word, ie, 494th timestep. At last it gives you H494 and C494 (C494 discarded and calculated newly for each sentence).\n",
    "\n",
    "This H494 goes ahead, which gives us prediction of review\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "**This process is done for each sentence** \n",
    "\n",
    "(sentence goes whole, then each 10D vector is fed word by word to LSTM, which at last timestep gives H494, which gives review prediction)\n",
    "\n",
    "**-------**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "91f5e9dc-16f8-41da-84a0-7f132165a1ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Each LSTM neuron gives one Ht, so after LSTM layer you have (32,1) vector, consisting of Ht values of each LSTM neuron\n",
    "\n",
    "Each Ht is fed to 5 output neurons of the output layer, which give probability of review rating.\n",
    "\n",
    "(1x32) * (32x5) = (1x5)    [ 32x5 is the weight matrix between LSTM and output layer ]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cf3d0fcc-7499-4932-bd3f-ef74fdf27b00",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "**No one-hot encoding is explicitly done in memory for the full vocab size.**\n",
    "\n",
    "**Instead, the embedding layer internally works as a lookup table of shape (vocab_size, embedding_dim).**\n",
    "\n",
    "**If your input is an integer 3, the layer fetches the 3rd row of that table directly — no multiplication with a huge one-hot vector.**"
   ]
  },
